video_title: Alex Svanevik - 30,000 Hours with AI: How We Made Our Team AI Native - SuperAI Singapore 2025
description:
Learn more about SuperAI: superai.com
Follow us on X: x.com/superai_conf

Keynote: 30,000 Hours with AI: How We Made Our Team AI Native

Speaker:
Alex Svanevik, Co-Founder and CEO @ Nansen

Stage: WEKA Stage
#superai #nansen #ai #web3data #dataanalytics 

Recorded on 18 June 2025

transcript.aggregated_text: 18 months ago we set out on this journey because we understood that AI is one of the most important techn technological forces in the world and we wanted to embrace it with full force so before I dive into that let me give you a little bit of context on who I am and little bit of context on our company i like to say that I was in AI before it was cool i took a degree in AI in 2010 that's 15 years ago people did not realize that AI was actually a degree that was at Edinburgh University where Jeff Hinton also took his PhD i then moved on to start a data science consultancy and I worked with data science for many years both as a data scientist myself and as a data scientist manager later on and then in 2017 I fell down the rabbit hole of crypto i learned about Ethereum and I went all in i moved from Barcelona to Hong Kong and I joined a crypto startup there to make a long story short that didn't go very well but I ended up founding Nonsen as a result in 2019 and just so you have a bit of context on the company in terms of the size and who we are we're a series B stage company we are around 80 people we have people across 30 countries remote first and we've raised $88 million from investors such as A16Z Excel GIC and many others now why do we exist why does this company exist we believe that every asset will eventually be tokenized that means it's going to be onchain on a blockchain and as a result billions of people are going to become owners in other words we believe in a future that is the opposite of what the World Economic Forum tells you that you will own nothing and be happy we believe you will own something and be happy and blockchains are going to become the new financial fabric in this world this is our vision this is the world we want to create and our role in it is to help onchain investors and also onchain builders surface the signal so that we can help create winners this is basically the master plan of our company if we can help them do that they will reinvest into the industry we will get great products great infrastructure built and the future of finance becomes a reality that is why the company exists and that's our mission now like I said before we believe that AI is one of the most important technological paradigm changes and the other one is onchain i don't think I have to convince you that much on AI uh and I won't spend the time convincing you on onchain either but let's start talking a bit more about AI 18 months ago we set our AI aspiration to be that we want to make this company an AI trailblazer in two ways both for product innovation and also for organizational productivity as a company that means it's going to be harder for others to keep up with us and also as individuals in this company we will be better equipped to thrive in this future and so if we start with the product side where we've made quite a lot of advances in the last year there are three essential pillars for the product strategy and how we think about AI number one we have a deep data moat so for those of you who don't know our product essentially what we do is help onchain investors figure out what's happening on blockchains in real time across any chain that they care about and an important point here is that you need to understand what the different addresses are if you just get data from a public node or a blockchain you won't know what the different addresses are and with our product we've labeled addresses in fact we've lab labeled about half a billion addresses with entity information behavioral information etc and essentially we are the best in the world at doing this so this is the first part and we use AI and I'll show you an example of that afterwards to do this job we also want to create fast and fluid interfaces and I used the um the photo of Harrison Ford from Bladeunner because there's a scene when he talks to his TV and he's panning in zooming out maybe you've seen the movie and we want to create a similar user experience with Nunson you can talk to the data and in 1 second you can answer things that would otherwise take you hours of research and finally personalization is a big component we want to make sure that when you explore blockchains you get personalized alpha you get personalized information based on your portfolio and your preference and so let me show you one of these examples in action deep research on wallets if you look up an address you paste in any address um a blockchain address into our product you go in command K search bar paste in the address you get an overview of the address but sometimes we might not have that much information about the address and that's when you can click the new deep research button literally what this does is it sends out a team of AI agents to investigate what the address is and after a couple of minutes you get a report it might be a little bit hard to read in this case I've looked up the Donald Trump Trump memecoin deployer and you get a summary of what this address actually is across lots of different dimensions we look at what it's doing on chain we look at mentions on the web we look at mentions in code repositories on GitHub and so on and so forth mentions on social media and then the agent team forms a committee and gives a confidence score about what we know about this address and gives you all of the background and research that they've done over those minutes and so this is what it looks like in the product right you go over you click the deep research button and you get this full report a TLDDR at the top an executive summary and then you get deeper information on lots of different dimensions it's pretty cool and we launched this in the product last week we also have a research agent that's powered by our MCP model context protocol which means that you can bring nonsson into chatbt into claude and so on and so forth and this is going to launch next month and I'm extremely excited about it now I said I was here last year talking about how we made our team AI native so let's shift gears and talk a bit about the organizational aspect which maybe is more relevant for many of you last time I was here I talked about how we used a weekly survey to measure each individual's time spent with AI the concept was that becoming AI native is a little bit like learning a new language or going to the gym if you just show up and do the work the results are going to come and we spent 5,000 hours in the first quarter we spent 6,000 hours in the next quarter and maybe now you understand why this talk is called 30,000 hours i would estimate that over the 18 months we spent far more than 30,000 hours collectively working with AI in different ways and let me share a little bit about what we have changed since last year so one thing we have changed is we used to do a survey based approach we just asked our employees with a slack form how many hours have you spent with AI which tools have you used and which use cases did you use it for so it's very much trust based but it works for a company our size now we actually look directly at the tool usage and so this is a chart that shows how much our engineers use cursor and as you can see every month pretty much we spend more time using cursor our engineers at this point spend an incredible amount of time with cursor and I think the whole engineering and coding experience has radically transformed for the team another shift we've made is to you know look not just at inputs but also the outputs that are created and so some stats here on a monthly basis we have more than a million lines of code edited or created by AI of course that's not the best metric if you're an engineer to be to be measuring on its own we have 38% of our poll requests be reviewed approved and deployed by an agent so it gives a confidence score of how complex the pull request is and if it's not too complex and it can do it without any intervention it approves it and auto deploys it into production and as a result we've reduced our median lead time for change by 95% so those of you in the audience who are familiar with Dora metrics for engineering productivity metrics uh you will probably recognize lead time this is basically how much time it takes from when you start fixing something or creating something to seeing it in production we also have clawed code living in our Slack and so this might be a little bit hard to read but essentially someone brings up that this button is probably placed in the wrong place and I say "Yes it should be at this other place." And one of our engineers invokes Claude Code cloud code understands the thread goes out creates a pull request another agent approves it and now the button has been moved from the right part of the screen to the left part of the screen and so when we first did this I was very happy because I felt I could take credit for that code change being the one who proposed the solution so prepare for a world where CEOs will take credit for new code changes in your codebase we've also moved from output to outcomes right and if you think about productivity we're in a very special place right now in Singapore where we where we've seen a remarkable journey in GDP per capita since the 1960s and we think about productivity at a very large scale in a similar manner for our company what is our GDP per capita or what does it look like over the the last 18 months since we started this journey it is tripled when I say GDP per capita here I mean annual revenues per headcount but that is effectively the same as GDP per capita and so how did we do it well we have some AI principles for organizational productivity and these are pretty basic number one try AI first if you have a problem you try AI first surprisingly this is something that is not very intuitive for people but you should always try AI first make AI a team member you just saw claude code you have to make sure that the AI is and the agents are present where the rest of the human team members are and that's also the third principle and fourth you have to proactively make sure that the team upskills on AI i don't think you can rely on training top down upskilling I think is a better word because it means people take more responsibility themselves in order to use AI tools and get familiar with them but maybe the most important thing that I think everyone has to do is to build an AI culture you might know the quote culture eats strategy for breakfast and I deeply believe that to be true culture is incredibly important and making sure that you create a work environment where the default is that you work with AI is incredibly important i think we live in a world now where you have a biodal AI nativeness distribution lots of companies are laggers they are fearful of AI they're worried about security risks and so on and you have a small bell curve that's very AI native that's really just accelerating in their use and you have to think about which of those two bell curves you want to be in on that scale so it's all culture it always has been thank you very much
